why exactly it is bhaving like this ?

This is actually a very important SSH concept that every DevOps/Cloud engineer encounters.

What happened?

When Ansible first tried connecting to the servers:

ansible all -m ping

SSH saw these hosts for the first time:

172.31.19.177
172.31.19.227
172.31.20.209

and asked:

The authenticity of host can't be established.
Are you sure you want to continue connecting?

You typed:

yes

However, Ansible was opening multiple SSH connections in parallel.

Think of it like:

SSH Session 1 -> 172.31.19.177
SSH Session 2 -> 172.31.19.227
SSH Session 3 -> 172.31.20.209

When you typed "yes", one connection completed successfully and stored its fingerprint in:

~/.ssh/known_hosts

At that moment only:

172.31.19.177

was added.

You confirmed this:

cat ~/.ssh/known_hosts

Output showed only:

172.31.19.177 ssh-ed25519 ....
172.31.19.177 ecdsa-sha2-nistp256 ....

No entries existed for:

172.31.19.227
172.31.20.209

So Ansible failed on those hosts with:

Host key verification failed
Why did manual SSH fix it?

When you ran:

ssh 172.31.20.209

SSH asked:

Are you sure you want to continue connecting?

You typed:

yes

Then SSH stored:

172.31.20.209

inside:

~/.ssh/known_hosts

Similarly for:

ssh 172.31.19.227

Now all 3 fingerprints existed in known_hosts.

What SSH is protecting you from

Suppose yesterday:

172.31.20.209 = Server A

Today someone destroys Server A and launches:

172.31.20.209 = Server B

with the same IP but a different SSH key.

Without verification, SSH would blindly trust the new machine.

With host key checking, SSH says:

Wait...
The machine at this IP is presenting a different identity.
Are you sure?

This prevents:

Man-in-the-middle attacks
DNS spoofing
Connecting to the wrong server
Accidental access to a recreated EC2 instance
How enterprises handle this

For lab environments:

host_key_checking = False

in:

/etc/ansible/ansible.cfg

Then Ansible auto-accepts fingerprints.

For production:

Host keys are preloaded.
SSH certificates are used.
Host key checking remains enabled.
About the Python warning
Platform linux on host ... is using the discovered Python interpreter at /usr/bin/python3.9

This is only a warning.

Ansible detected:

/usr/bin/python3.9

on the remote hosts and used it.

The ping succeeded:

"ping": "pong"

so there is no problem.

Real-time interview question

If an interviewer asks:

"Why did Ansible show Host key verification failed?"

A strong answer is:

"Ansible uses SSH underneath. The target servers' SSH fingerprints were not present in the control node's ~/.ssh/known_hosts file. SSH host key verification blocked the connection. After manually accepting the host keys, Ansible was able to connect successfully."

That's exactly what happened in your case.


