You have two completely different concepts that happen to use the same names (a, b, c).

1. Inventory Groups (Hosts)

In /etc/ansible/hosts:

[a]
172.31.20.209

[b]
172.31.19.177

[c]
172.31.19.227

These groups decide which servers Ansible targets.

Example:

hosts: a

means:

Run on 172.31.20.209 only
2. Tags (Tasks)

In your playbook:

- name: installing git
  tags: a

- name: installing maven
  tags: b

- name: create user
  tags: c

These tags decide which tasks execute.

Example:

ansible-playbook tags.yaml --tags c

means:

Run only the "create user" task

on all hosts matched by hosts:.

Visualize it like this

Hosts = WHERE

hosts: all
172.31.20.209
172.31.19.177
172.31.19.227

Tags = WHAT

--tags c
Only create user task
Example
ansible-playbook tags.yaml --tags c

Interpretation:

WHERE?  -> hosts: all
          3 servers

WHAT?   -> tag c
          create user task only

Result:

Create user on all 3 servers
Another example
ansible-playbook tags.yaml --tags a --limit b

Interpretation:

WHERE?  -> group b
          172.31.19.177

WHAT?   -> tag a
          install git

Result:

Install git only on 172.31.19.177

A common practice in real projects is to avoid naming tags a, b, c. Instead use meaningful names:

tags:
  - install

tags:
  - configure

tags:
  - deploy

tags:
  - restart

This makes playbooks much easier to understand and maintain.

